# CompliTrace Repository Analysis (Dense Technical Deep Dive)

## 0. Purpose of this document

This document is a deep technical analysis of the entire CompliTrace repository as currently implemented, intended to explain **exactly how the software audit flow works end-to-end** across ingestion, parsing, sectioning, retrieval, LLM processing, deterministic legal gating, publication controls, review surfaces, export contracts, PDF generation, frontend presentation normalization, and observability.

It is intentionally exhaustive and implementation-centric.

---

## 1. Repository topology and runtime architecture

### 1.1 High-level modules

The repo is organized into service applications:

- `apps/ingestion-service`: Upload + PDF parsing + section extraction + document persistence.
- `apps/knowledge-service`: GDPR chunk indexing + vector retrieval APIs.
- `apps/orchestration-service`: Audit lifecycle + agentic section loop + legal qualification + finding persistence + publication/review/report APIs.
- `apps/frontend`: React UI consuming ingestion/orchestration APIs.
- `infra/*`: Prometheus/Grafana config.
- `scripts/*`: GDPR ingestion/validation utilities.
- `data/*`: Raw and processed GDPR corpus data.

### 1.2 Container orchestration

`docker-compose.yml` defines:

- PostgreSQL (system of record for documents/audits/findings/reports)
- Qdrant (vector store)
- Knowledge service (8002)
- Ingestion service (8001)
- Orchestration service (8003)
- Prometheus + Grafana
- Frontend (5173)

Environment variables control model provider names, API keys, LLM budgets, corpus metadata, report directory, and CORS.

### 1.3 Data and control plane boundaries

- **Data plane**: Document text and extracted sections originate in ingestion; retrieval evidence originates in knowledge; persisted findings are authored by orchestration.
- **Control plane**: Orchestration’s final disposition map and publication validator decide whether any finding is publishable or blocked/internal.

